:::summary
Planets are large celestial bodies that orbit a star, have sufficient gravity to assume a roughly spherical shape, and have cleared the neighborhood around their orbit of other debris. Our solar system contains eight officially recognized planets — each one a unique world with its own character, beauty, and mystery. From the scorched surface of Mercury to the icy reaches of Neptune, the planets testify to the extraordinary variety of God's creative work and have fascinated astronomers, philosophers, and ordinary stargazers for thousands of years.
:::

